" class=3D" wp-image-1176 aligncenter" src=3D"https://heytutor.com/wp-conte=
nt/uploads/2024/08/StudentsR99K_0-300x214.png" alt=3D"" width=3D"371" heigh=
t=3D"265"><br>
</span></h3>
<h3 dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 10pt; margin-bottom:=
 0pt;"><span style=3D"font-size: 16pt; font-family: Cambria, serif; color: =
#000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: norm=
al; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; =
white-space: pre-wrap;">How to Calculate Percentage Error<br>
</span></h3>
<p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 1=
0pt;"><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; b=
ackground-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-va=
riant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space=
: pre-wrap;">A percentage error provides an easy-to-understand measure of e=
rror margins. It lets you know how big an error is. For instance, a 3-perce=
nt error value means that your measured figure is very close to the actual =
value. On the other hand, a 50-percent margin means your measurement is a l=
ong way from the real value. If you end up with a 50-percent error, you pro=
bably need to change your measuring instrument.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h3 dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 10pt; margin-bottom:=
 0pt;"><span style=3D"font-size: 16pt; font-family: Cambria, serif; color: =
#000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: norm=
al; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; =
white-space: pre-wrap;">Why Do We Calculate Percentage Error?<br>
</span></h3>
<p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 1=
0pt;"><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; b=
ackground-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-va=
riant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space=
: pre-wrap;">There are many reasons for calculating percentage errors. Engi=
neers use it to determine the precision of a measuring instrument. Within t=
he finance sector, statisticians and data analysts rely on it to verify if =
a data set is progressing in the right direction. Outside the workspace, we=
 use percentage errors for lots of everyday tasks. For instance, if you=E2=
=80=99re baking a cake and the recipe calls for four and a half teaspoons o=
f sugar, you could simply round it off. You could indulge your sweet tooth =
by adding five teaspoons or opt for four spoons. Either option would be abo=
ut a 10% error margin=E2=80=94and still lead to tasty results.</span></p>
<h3 dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: =
10pt;"><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; =
background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-v=
ariant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-spac=
e: pre-wrap;"><strong>Note: If the measured value is the same as the actual=
 value, then the percentage error is zero.<br>
</strong><br>
</span><span style=3D"font-size: 16pt; font-family: Cambria,serif; color: #=
4f81bd; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: norma=
l; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; w=
hite-space: pre-wrap;"><span style=3D"color: #000000;">How to Calculate Per=
centage Error</span><br>
</span><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; =
background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-v=
ariant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-spac=
e: pre-wrap;">Calculating the percentage error is a lot less complicated th=
an </span><a style=3D"text-decoration: none;" href=3D"https://heytutor.com/=
blog/how-to-calculate-standard-deviation/"><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; =
font-family: Arial; color: #0000ff; background-color: transparent; font-wei=
ght: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: underl=
ine; -webkit-text-decoration-skip: none; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; ve=
rtical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">calculating standard deviat=
ion</span></a><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #0=
00000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal;=
 font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; whi=
te-space: pre-wrap;">. You only need to complete several quick steps.</span=
></h3>
<p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0=
pt;" role=3D"presentation"><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Ari=
al; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-s=
tyle: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: =
baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">1. Subtract the actual value from the est=
imated value</span></p>
<p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0=
pt;" role=3D"presentation"><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Ari=
al; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-s=
tyle: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: =
baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">2. Divide the results from step 1 with th=
e real value</span></p>
<p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 1=
0pt;" role=3D"presentation"><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Ar=
ial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-=
style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align:=
 baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">3. Multiply the results by 100 to find t=
he total percentage</span></p>
<p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 1=
0pt;"><strong><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #0=
00000; background-color: transparent; font-style: normal; font-variant: nor=
mal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap=
;">All of this is summed up with the formula:</span></strong></p>
<p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 1=
0pt;" role=3D"presentation"><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Ar=
ial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-=
style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align:=
 baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">=E2=80=93 Percentage Error =3D ((Estimat=
ed Number =E2=80=93 Actual Number)/ Actual number) x 100</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; back=
ground-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-vari=
ant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: =
pre-wrap;">To see how the calculation works, let=E2=80=99s look at a quick =
example.</span></p>
<p><strong><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #0000=
00; background-color: transparent; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal=
; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">=
While measuring the layout for a pool, a landscaper accidentally records 8m=
. What is the percentage error if the actual length is 10m?</span></strong>=
</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; back=
ground-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-varia=
nt: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: p=
re-wrap;">To solve for this, we=E2=80=99ll use the formula:</span></p>
<p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 1=
0pt;"><span style=3D"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; b=
ackground-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-va=
riant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space=
: pre-wrap;">Percentage Error =3D ((Estimated Number =E2=80=93 Actual Numbe=
r)/ Actual number) x 100</span></p>
<ul>
<li dir=3D"ltr" role=3D"presentation">Where the Actual Value =3D 10m</li>
<li dir=3D"ltr" role=3D"presentation">And the estimated value =3D 8m.</li>
</ul>
<p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"line-height: 1.3800000000000001; margin-top: 10pt; =
margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt; font-family: 'Times Ne=
w Roman'; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold;=
 font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-=
align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">Step 1. Subtract the actual value =
from the estimated value</span></p>
<ul>
<li dir=3D"ltr">8m =E2=80=93 10m =3D -2m</li>
</ul>
<p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"line-height: 1.3800000000000001; margin-top: 10pt; =
margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt; font-family: 'Times Ne=
w Roman'; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold;=
 font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-=
align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">Step 2. Divide the results with th=
e actual value</span></p>
<ul>
<li dir=3D"ltr">2m/10m =3D -0.2</li>
</ul>
<p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"line-height: 1.3800000000000001; margin-top: 10pt; =
margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt; font-family: 'Times Ne=
w Roman'; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold;=
 font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-=
align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">Step 3. To find the percentage err=
